\par\pard\plain \fi691\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 To foster these in another (including yourself) is to do good. To harm them is evil. Simple enough, right? I don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t claim these as the highest authority, only as a system that with encourage the flourishing of abundant life throughout our world. It seems that, on the highest level, there is no Good nor Evil, only the Absolute that transcends. At each level of its transcendence there may exist both, but as its perspective engulfs the entire situation the drama of close proximity fades. We humans don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t see the cellular ecology as dramatic, but to our tissues the invasion of predatory bacteria is an all-out war. We see with understanding and acceptance of our body dramas and they fade...until something potent wells up and we are swept along in the drama as well.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Seeing and stepping out of the drama is the key to transcending good and evil. Not that you should necessarily do so \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  good serves an important function of keeping you alive and healthy, while evil serves to evolve, strengthen, and cull/release certain forces from your world. The problem is, as always, due to imbalance. Too much of a good thing is still bad, and too much bad is...well, still worse.}}